{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Baruch A. Levine | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1930|07|10|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Cleveland, Ohio]] | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = | period = | occupation = | boards = board member of the Society of Biblical Literature and Exegesis<!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation - e.g. "Editoral board of The Journal of Sociology" --> | known_for = | spouse = | children = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | era = | language = | discipline = Biblical studies<!-- Major academic discipline - e.g. Physicist, Sociologist, New Testament scholar, Ancient Near Eastern Linguist --> | sub_discipline = <!-- Academic discipline specialist area - e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist --> | movement = <!-- Should match the idiologial movement or denomination (for religious), "school" of thought etc. (e.g. "Anglican", "Postmodernist", "Socialist" or "Green" etc. -->
| education = | alma_mater = [[Brandeis University]] (Pd.D.)<!-- will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution. --> | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | main_interests = Biblical Interpretation | workplaces = | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influences = | influenced = | awards = Guggenheim Fellowship for Humanities, US & Canada | website = | footnotes = }} '''Baruch Abraham Levine''', (born July 10, 1930) [[Cleveland, Ohio]] is the Skirball Professor Emeritus of Bible and Ancient Near Eastern Studies at [[New York University]].<ref name=Bloom>{{cite web|title=Baruch A. Levine's Bloomsbury author entry|work=bloomsbury.com|url=http://www.bloomsbury.com/author/baruch-a-levine|access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=nyu>{{cite web|title=Baruch A. Levine's NY University faculty entry|work=NYU.edu|url=http://ancientstudies.as.nyu.edu/page/faculty|access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref>
Levine was educated at Case Western Reserve University and gained his Ph.D. at [[Brandeis University]] in (1962) and write mainly in the fields of Biblical studies and middle eastern studies.<ref name=Bloom/>
Levine wrote the ''JPS Torah Commentary: Leviticus'' commentary, the book ''In the presence of the Lord'' and the commentaries ''Numbers 1-20'' and ''Numbers 21-36'' in the [[Anchor Bible Series|Anchor Yale Bible]] series.<ref name=Bloom/>
He was president of the [[American Oriental Society]], the Association for Jewish Studies and the Biblical Colloquium. He also sat on the board member of the [[Society of Biblical Literature and Exegesis]].<ref name=Bloom/>
He was awarded the Guggenheim Fellowship for Humanities, US & Canada.
