{{Multiple issues| {{tone|date=November 2008}} {{original research|date=November 2008}} {{notability|date=November 2008}} }}
A '''Minister of Everything''', sometimes also called '''Minister for Everything''', refers to a Minister who wields great and wide-reaching power in the government, usually as the head of a powerful and influential ministry (often a "super ministry" combining two or more portfolios), but also can influence government machinery outside his direct control. The title is unofficial, and often assigned by the media or other political figures. Ministers who are seen as holding the title are often regarded as the second most powerful person in the government after the head of government, and often (but not always) this position is cemented by holding the official title of Deputy Prime Minister/Deputy Premier/Deputy First Minister etc. The term can also be used as a criticism of heads of government who take a more hands on approach in governing and give ministers less independence, or a head of government who hold additional powerful cabinet portfolios.
==Examples== List of figures who have been considered of holding the title:
* [[C.D. Howe]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadaonline.about.com/od/canadaww2/p/cdhowe.htm|title=C.D. Howe Mobilized Canada for World War II|publisher=}}</ref> Canada, [[Liberal Party of Canada]], at various times served as Minister of Railways and Canals, Minister of Transport, Minister of Munitions and Supply, Minister of Reconstruction, Minister of Trade and Commerce. * [[Walter Murray Gibson]],<ref>{{cite journal|jstor=1873708|title=Review of The Fantastic Life of Walter Murray Gibson: Hawaii's Minister of everything|first=James A.|last=Zimmerman|date=1 January 1988|publisher=|journal=The American Historical Review|volume=93|issue=5|pages=1407–1408|doi=10.2307/1873708}}</ref> [[Hawaiian Kingdom]] Prime Minister, also served as minister of foreign affairs and minister of war. * [[John Prescott]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/1997/may/06/labour.uk|title=Minister for everything|first=Ewen|last=Macaskill|date=6 May 1997|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> United Kingdom, [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Deputy Prime Minister and Secretary of State for the Environment, Transport and the Regions. * [[John Swinney]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publicfinance.co.uk/features_details.cfm?News_id=32392|title=Minister for everything, interview with John Swinney, by David Scott - Public Finance|publisher=}}</ref> Scotland, [[Scottish National Party]], Cabinet Secretary for Finance and Sustainable Growth. * [[Wendy Alexander]], Scotland, [[Scottish Labour Party]], Minister of Communities, and Minister for Enterprise, Transport and Lifelong Learning. * [[Hazel Blears]],<ref>{http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article552853.ece</ref> United Kingdom, [[Labour Party UK|Labour]] Served as Labour Party Chair, Minister without Portfolio, and Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government. * [[Don Mazankowski]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id%3D2091 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-08-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114004630/http://www.pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?id=2091 |archivedate=2010-01-14 |df= }}</ref> Canada, [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada]], Deputy Prime Minister, served at various times as Minister of Transport, President of the Treasury Board, Minister of Agriculture, Government House Leader, and Minister of Finance. * [[George Smitherman]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/News/Columnists/Blizzard_Christina/2008/06/20/5932856-sun.php|title=Columnists - Opinion - Toronto Sun|publisher=}}</ref> Ontario, [[Ontario Liberal Party]], Deputy Premier, served as Minister of Health and then Minister of Energy and Infrastructure. * [[John Manley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/1773338.stm|title=Canadian PM undercuts rivals|date=21 January 2002|publisher=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Canada, [[Liberal Party of Canada]], served as Minister of Industry, Minister of Foreign Affairs, Minister of Finance, and Deputy Prime Minister. * [[Dean Barrow]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanpedrosun.net/old/08-074.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-08-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100227131826/http://www.sanpedrosun.net/old/08-074.html |archivedate=2010-02-27 |df= }}</ref> Belize, [[United Democratic Party (Belize)|United Democratic Party]], Prime Minister of Belize, also Attorney General, Minister of Foreign Affairs, and Minister of National Security. * [[Shimon Peres]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1316/is_n10_v21/ai_8139717 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-08-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050408051656/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1316/is_n10_v21/ai_8139717 |archivedate=2005-04-08 |df= }}</ref> Israel, [[Labor Party (Israel)|Labour Party]] and [[Kadima]], at times served as President of Israel, Prime Minister, Transportation Minister, Religious Services Minister, Internal Affairs Minister, Immigrant Absorption Minister, Defense Minister, Foreign Affairs Minister, Finance Minister, and Communications Minister. * [[Russ Hinze]],<ref>[[Parliament of Queensland|Queensland Parliamentary]] [[#Hansard|Hansard]], 16 July 1991, p. 6, 10, 14</ref> Australia, [[National Party of Australia|National Party]], served as Queensland Minister for Main Roads and Local Government (1974-1987), Minister for Racing (1980-1987) & Minister for Police (1980-1982) in the government of [[Sir Joh Bjelke-Petersen]].
